Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Squirrel pox is a viral disease affecting red squirrels, killing
them within 15 days of infection. It is carried by grey squirrels,
which show no symptoms of disease, so that they continue to thrive
and breed while carrying the virus. It is thought to have been
brought into Britain with grey squirrels introduced into southern
England from America in the early 20th century. Several pox-like
disease outbreaks in red squirrels were recorded over the decades,
but the virus was first confirmed during a disease outbreak in East
Anglia in the 1980s and it has since worked its way steadily northwards.

For further information, subscribers are referred to the website of
the Scottish Squirrel Survey at
<http://www.scottishsquirrelsurvey.co.uk/index.html>
and to Mod.TG commentary in ProMED-mail posting 20070519.1594. - Mod.AS

The Scottish Borders in southeastern Scotland can be located on the map at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/europe/united_kingdom.gif>. - CopyEd.MJ]
